6.2 says that strings over 100 characters should **not** be split into new lines. 18.12 says they should be. Both provide contradicting examples.

**6.2**:

```
// good
const errorMessage = 'This is a super long error that was thrown because of Batman. When you stop to think about how Batman had anything to do with this, you would get nowhere fast.';
```

**18.12**:

```
// bad
const foo = 'Whatever national crop flips the window. The cartoon reverts within the screw. Whatever wizard constrains a helpful ally. The counterpart ascends!';
```

This previously gave the example:

```
[1, 2, 3].map(number => {
  const nextNumber = number + 1;
  `A string containing the ${nextNumber}.`;
});
```

However, in both node 5, and node 6, this example doesn't actually work. It certainly is "bad" but not for the given reason. It also gave me (and perhaps others) the impression that the final statement was implicitly returned when it's not.

```
$  docker run -it --rm node:6 node
> const test = [1, 2, 3].map(number => {
... const nextNumber = number + 1;
... `A string containing the ${nextNumber}.`;
... });
undefined
> test
[ undefined, undefined, undefined ]
>
(To exit, press ^C again or type .exit)
>

$  docker run -it --rm node:5 node
> const test = [1, 2, 3].map(number => {
... const nextNumber = number + 1;
... `A string containing the ${nextNumber}.`;
... });
undefined
> test
[ undefined, undefined, undefined ]
>
(To exit, press ^C again or type .exit)
>
```

I've chosen another example that does work and seems "bad" based on the explanation given in the guide.

```
& docker run -it --rm node:5 node
> let test = [1, 2, 3].map(number => { return `A string containing the ${number}.`; });
undefined
> test
[ 'A string containing the 1.',
  'A string containing the 2.',
  'A string containing the 3.' ]
>
(To exit, press ^C again or type .exit)
>});


$ docker run -it --rm node:6 node
> let test = [1, 2, 3].map(number => { return `A string containing the ${number}.`; });
undefined
> test
[ 'A string containing the 1.',
  'A string containing the 2.',
  'A string containing the 3.' ]
>
(To exit, press ^C again or type .exit)
>});
```

Just wanted to clarify something that was confusing to me and perhaps others reading.

[7.1](https://github.com/airbnb/javascript#functions--declarations) states that the following is "bad":

```
// bad
const foo = function () {};
```

However, [7.11](https://github.com/airbnb/javascript#functions--signature-spacing) states the following is "good":

```
// good
const x = function () {};
```

I understand [7.11](https://github.com/airbnb/javascript#functions--signature-spacing) is talking about spacing alone, but the fact that the example used was what _not_ to do in the previous section [7.1](https://github.com/airbnb/javascript#functions--declarations) seemed strange.

The following simplified code produces a `no-cond-assign` error on the first `if` caused by the assignments in the fat-arrow function within:

``` js
'use strict';
const arr = [1, 2, 3];

if (arr.some(val => {
  let b = true;
  if (val === 2) {
    b = false;
  }
  return b;
})) console.log('returned true');
```

I linted the code above with the `eslint:recommended` style with the `"no-cond-assign": 2` rule explicitly added and also initializing my eslint config file through `eslint --init` and picking airbnb, google and standard styles.  The error **is only produced when using the airbnb style**, that is why I am reporting it here.  It also happens using `eslint-config-airbnb-base` and changing the eslintrc file to extend `airbnb-base`.

Here is the package.json

``` json
{
  "name": "no-cond-assign",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "description": "no-cond-assign",
  "main": "index.js",
  "scripts": {
    "test": "node index.js",
    "lint": "eslint . || exit 0"
  },
  "author": "",
  "license": "MIT",
  "devDependencies": {
    "eslint": "^3.2.2",
    "eslint-config-airbnb": "^10.0.0",
    "eslint-plugin-react": "^6.0.0"
  }
}
```

and eslint config:

``` js
module.exports = {
    "extends": "airbnb",
    "plugins": [
        "react"
    ],
    // Not relevant, just to avoid unnecessary noise:
    "rules": {
      strict: 0,
      "no-console": 0
    }
};
```

Add a topic, maybe in section 7 (Functions), about using spread operator `...` instead of `apply()`. Like:

// bad
var args = [1, 2, 3, 4];
Math.max.apply(Math, args);

// good
var args = [1, 2, 3, 4];
Math.max(...args);

Related ESlint rule: `prefer-spread`

Don know if worth adding this, because my reason would be just: it is cleaner this way.
